{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a63b0af8-8854-45d6-b888-e8b3330ed75a","content":"Here's what you need:\n\n## 1. Add a shared `Directory.Build.props` (at the solution root)\n\nThis sets the properties consistently across all three projects:\n\n```xml\n<Project>\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n    <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n| Property | Why |\n|---|---|\n| `EnableMSTestRunner` | Activates the MTP runner built into MSTest 3.8.0 |\n| `OutputType` → `Exe` | Required — each test project becomes a self-contained executable |\n| `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` | Lets `dotnet test` work with MTP on .NET 8 SDK |\n\n## 2. Add the TRX package to each `.csproj`\n\nThe VSTest `--logger trx` flag doesn't apply under MTP. Add this package instead:\n\n```xml\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" Version=\"1.*\" />\n```\n\nOr put it in a `Directory.Packages.props` / the same `Directory.Build.props` if you prefer centralizing it.\n\n## 3. Update the CI command\n\n```diff\n- dotnet test --logger trx\n+ dotnet test -- --report-trx\n```\n\nEverything after `--` is forwarded to Microsoft.Testing.Platform. The `--report-trx` flag tells the TRX report extension to emit `.trx` files (written to `TestResults/` by default, same as before).\n\n**Summary of changes:**\n- **0 edits** to test source code\n- **1 new file** — `Directory.Build.props` at solution root (3 properties)\n- **1 package added** per project — `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport`\n- **1 CI line changed** — `--logger trx` → `-- --report-trx`","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"959d7bb8-bfb4-4f10-b45c-0983bed1f28a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to migrate 3 MSTest 3.8.0 test projects from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP). They're on .NET 8 SDK and use `dotnet test --logger trx` in CI.\n\nLet me provide a concise, accurate answer based on my knowledge of MSTest 3.8.0 and Microsoft.Testing.Platform.\n\nKey points for MSTest 3.8.0 migration to MTP:\n\n1. **Project-level changes**: Set `<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>` and `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` in each test project (or a shared `Directory.Build.props`).\n\n\n2. **For consistency across all 3 projects**, using a `Directory.Build.props` file is the cleanest approach.\n3. **TRX reporting**: The `--logger trx` flag doesn't work with MTP the same way. Instead, you need the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` NuGet package and use `--report-trx` in your CI command, or configure it in the test project's properties.\n4. **CI command update**: The command changes from `dotnet test --logger trx` to something like `dotnet test --report-trx` depending on how you configure the TRX extension.\n\nFor MSTest 3.8.0 specifically, I need to account for the fact that it has built-in Microsoft.Testing.Platform support. You'd set `<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>` and `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` in the project file, then add the TRX report package for report generation. The `dotnet test` wrapper still works, but the arguments and configuration differ from the older VSTest approach. For .NET 8 SDK, there's a compatibility layer to handle this. When MTP is enabled, the project needs `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` to function as a self-contained executable. For `dotnet test` compatibility on .NET 8 SDK, I need to add `<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>` to bridge the gap. For TRX reporting, I'll add the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` NuGet package and use `--report-trx` instead of `--logger trx`, or pass `-- --report-trx` when using `dotnet test`. Now I'm setting up the shared configuration in Directory.Build.props...\n\nConfiguring project files...","outputTokens":1822,"requestId":"BD02:AA16B:1D5C79C:210376E:6A07C429"},"id":"1454919b-c0e1-4174-9394-21c788a05645","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:11:36.518Z","parentId":"239c05cc-30b5-43d7-91f9-4df63b0ced70"}
